Looking at this code, I need to identify the bug. Let me analyze the function carefully.

The issue is in this section:
```java
} else {
    // Need to copy to a separate buffer first
    TokenBuffer b2 = TokenBuffer.asCopyOfValue(p);
    tokens.writeFieldName(propName);
    tokens.append(b2);
    try {
        buffer.bufferAnyProperty(_anySetter, propName,
                _anySetter.deserialize(b2.asParserOnFirstToken(), ctxt));
    } catch (Exception e) {
        wrapAndThrow(e, _beanType.getRawClass(), propName, ctxt);
    }
    continue;
}
```

The problem is that when we have an `_anySetter`, we write the field name to `tokens`, but we never advance past the copied content. After handling the any-setter property, we should continue to the next token, but the loop will call `p.nextToken()` which may not correctly advance past the already-processed value.

Actually, looking more closely at the loop structure:
```java
for (; t == JsonToken.FIELD_NAME; t = p.nextToken()) {
    String propName = p.getCurrentName();
    p.nextToken(); // to point to value
    ...
}
```

After processing in the `_anySetter` block, we do `continue;`, which goes back to the loop condition where `t = p.nextToken()` is called. However, we've already consumed the value when creating `TokenBuffer.asCopyOfValue(p)`, so the parser is already positioned after the value. The `continue` statement correctly advances to the next iteration.

